{
  "title": "Securing ETL Jobs using FastAPI with Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This explainer demonstrates how to implement a secure Extract, Transform, Load (ETL) pipeline utilizing FastAPI and Python 3.12+, emphasizing authentication, authorization, and data encryption.",

  "key_points": [
    "Use FastAPI's built-in security features for authentication and authorization",
    "Implement data encryption using libraries such as PyCryptodome or cryptography",
    "Establish secure connections with databases like PostgreSQL using SSL/TLS",
    "Implement rate limiting to prevent abuse of the ETL API",
    "Follow best practices for input validation and error handling"
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\nfrom fastapi import FastAPI, Depends, HTTPException\napp = FastAPI()\nfrom jWTBearer import JWTBearer\njwt_bearer = JWTBearer(tokenUrl='token')\n\n@app.get('/etl', dependencies=[Depends(jwt_bearer.require)], response_model=ETLResponse)\ndef etl(current_user: dict = Depends(jwt_bearer.authenticate)):  # ETL function securely called with authenticated user data\n```"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "```\nfrom cryptography import pydes\ncipher = pydes.TripleDES(keys=my_key, mode=pydes.CBC, pad=None)\ndef encrypt(data):  # Example of data encryption using PyCryptodome\n    ciphertext = cipher.encrypt(data, None) \n    return base64.b64encode(ciphertext).decode('utf-8')\n\ndef decrypt(data):  # Decryption example\n    ciphertext = base64.b64decode(data)\n    return cipher.decrypt(ciphertext, None) \n```"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "Python 3.12+ is required for using f-strings and async/await features",
    "FastAPI version 0.76.0 or higher is recommended",
    "If using PyCryptodome, ensure you have version 3.14.1 or later"
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "Always validate user input to prevent SQL injection and other security vulnerabilities",
